<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1913-03-10T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1913-03-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="929" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d929">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/6606.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Consul at Ciudad
                                    Porfirio Díaz</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Ciudad Porfirio Díaz</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-03-10">
                                    <hi rend="italic">March 10, 1913</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>The Governor of Coahuila, at Monclova, and Colonel Carranza, here, have
                            just seized the rolling stock shops and their equipment and other
                            property of the Mexican National Railway lines here. Evidently they
                            intend to attempt to operate all the railroad and shops for the benefit
                            of the State cause.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Luther T. Ellsworth</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>